{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523596"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.23,0.07,0.43,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49059"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6528"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34088"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"913"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49059"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for follow-up of abnormal liver function tests. She has a history of injecting drug use in her twenties but has not injected for over 10 years. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no signs of chronic liver disease. Recent investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCV RNA: Detected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 78 U/L (0-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 65 U/L (0-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 38 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 220 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 1.0 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver elastography shows no evidence of significant fibrosis or cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monitor liver function tests","Perform HCV genotype testing","Commence interferon therapy","Commence direct-acting antiviral therapy","Refer for liver biopsy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management for this patient with chronic hepatitis C infection is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence direct-acting antiviral (DAA) therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. DAAs are now the standard of care for hepatitis C treatment, offering cure rates of over 95% with minimal side effects. They are recommended as first-line therapy for all patients with chronic hepatitis C, regardless of disease severity or genotype.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitoring liver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not recommended. Early treatment of hepatitis C can prevent progression to cirrhosis, liver failure, and hepatocellular carcinoma. There is no benefit in delaying treatment in a patient who is ready to start therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming HCV genotype testing\u003C/strong\u003E before initiating treatment is no longer routinely required in many cases. Pan-genotypic DAA regimens are now available that are effective against all hepatitis C genotypes, simplifying the treatment approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon-based therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended as first-line treatment for hepatitis C due to its lower efficacy, longer treatment duration, and significant side effect profile compared to DAAs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for liver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case. Non-invasive methods such as liver elastography (which has already been performed) are now preferred for assessing liver fibrosis. The elastography results show no evidence of significant fibrosis or cirrhosis, making a liver biopsy unwarranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, this patient should be started on a course of DAA therapy, typically lasting 8-12 weeks for patients without cirrhosis. Regular monitoring during and after treatment will be necessary to confirm cure (sustained virologic response) and to manage any potential side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Direct-acting antivirals (DAAs) are the first-line treatment for chronic hepatitis C infection, offering high cure rates with minimal side effects.","Treatment duration for hepatitis C with DAAs is typically 8-12 weeks for most patients without cirrhosis.","Genotype testing is no longer routinely required before initiating DAA therapy for hepatitis C in many cases."],"references":["Hepatitis C Virus Infection Consensus Statement Working Group. Australian recommendations for the management of hepatitis C virus infection: a consensus statement. In: Gastroenterological Society of Australia [online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.hepcguidelines.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/hepatitis-C-virus-infection-a-consensus-statement-2022.pdf","Thompson AJ. Australian recommendations for the management of hepatitis C virus infection: a consensus statement. Med J Aust. 2016 Apr 18;204(7):268-72. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27078601/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34088"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34088"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T12:01:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-23T12:01:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49059"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiqu